TI  - Cost allocation of Internet links: A game theoretical approach
T2  - INFORMATION-AN INTERNATIONAL INTERDISCIPLINARY JOURNAL
AB  - The Internet has been one of the most significant and influential achievements in the modem computing and telecommunications history. As more and more applications flood the Internet, the voluntary network will be unable to provide the capacity to meet the demand and therefore new and more powerful systems and networks will need to be constructed. As the Internet makes its transition from a partially subsidized service to a mainly commercial service with all costs recovered by direct charging, there is certainly a need for a model of how cost recovery and pricing should be structured. This paper focuses on determining a "fair" or "just" allocation of the costs of Internet links through either leased lines or the construction of new links. Two solution concepts of cooperative games, the Shapley value and the nucleolus are suggested to assign costs to a coalition of organizations that share some Internet links. The issue of simplification of the two solution concepts when the number of organizations is very large is also discussed. A simple numeric example is used to illustrate the configuration model and solution concepts of an Internet link cost allocation game.
