AU  - Kuo, WC
AU  - Chen, CH
AU  - Wang, CC
TI  - Unlocking sub-MW microgrids for ancillary services: A stochastic bilevel VPP framework with weighted Shapley allocation
T2  - ENERGY
AB  - The strict 1 MW participation threshold in ancillary service (AS) markets, such as Taiwan's, creates a binary entry barrier that excludes sub-megawatt microgrids (MGs). Although virtual power plants (VPPs) can aggregate these assets to meet the threshold, they face a key game-theoretic challenge: coalition instability driven by unfair profit allocation. Existing mechanisms are not designed for threshold-based markets. Standard Shapley-value schemes exhibit strong pivotality bias, over-rewarding large MGs for enabling market entry, while fluctuation-based methods over-penalize high-capacity assets for natural load variability. To address this gap, this study proposes an integrated VPP framework centered on a performance-aware weighted Shapley value (WSV). The WSV links each MG's revenue share to its contribution to system reliability rather than to capacity or volatility, producing more balanced and behavior-consistent allocations. The mechanism is embedded in a two-stage stochastic bilevel programming (2SS-BLP) model that co-optimizes VPP bidding and MG-level dispatch under uncertainty. The hierarchical structure is solved using a logic-based Benders decomposition (LBBD), ensuring computational tractability and preserving MG data privacy. Case studies under real AS market conditions show that the proposed framework increases total coalition revenue by over 40 % while achieving the lowest inequality among all tested schemes (Gini = 0.117, compared with 0.266 for the standard Shapley value and 0.244 for the fluctuation-based method). The WSV effectively mitigates free-rider behavior and over-penalization issues, providing a scalable and incentive-compatible pathway for integrating sub-MW MGs into thresholdconstrained AS markets.
