TY  - JOUR
AU  - Zhu, JX
AU  - Han, WJ
AU  - Dong, F
AU  - Shi, LX
TI  - Factors influencing 3PLs' willingness to adopt sustainable and resilient service strategies under climate change context
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Based on a systematic investigation into the operational challenges and response mechanisms of third-party logistics enterprises under climate change, this study analyzes 423 valid questionnaires from Chinese thirdparty logistics firms using an integrated Structural Equation Modeling, Random Forest Regression, and SHapley Additive exPlanations approach. The results show that four factors-Environmental and Physical Factors, Regulatory and Policy Factors, Market and Social Factors, and Economic Cost Factors-all exert significant positive effects on the adoption willingness of Sustainable and Resilient Service Strategies, with influence decreasing in that order. SHapley Additive exPlanations analysis further reveals non-linear interactions among these factors, underscoring the complex, multi-dimensional nature of corporate strategic decision-making. Theoretically, this work expands the interdisciplinary perspective linking sustainability and organizational resilience in supply chain management. Practically, it offers empirical support for third-party logistics strategic planning under climate risks and provides a reference for governments to develop more systematic and incentivebased environmental policy frameworks. The findings suggest a strategic shift among third-party logistics firms from short-term cost-oriented models toward long-term sustainable resilience, emphasizing adaptation to external risks and institutional responses, thereby highlighting the synergy between operational sustainability and systemic resilience amid growing climate uncertainty.
