TI  - Interpretable machine learning uncovers urban morphology-multi-flow coupling in metro hubs: a lightGBM-SHAP approach
T2  - TRANSPORTMETRICA B-TRANSPORT DYNAMICS
AB  - Urban hubs underpin sustainable city functioning, yet how urban morphology shapes multiple flows remains unclear. Using interpretable machine learning, this study analyzed 1,245 metro-station hubs in Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen. A Light Gradient Boosting Machine (LightGBM) model integrated with SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) quantified the nonlinear and threshold effects of seven morphological indicators on four flows-human, logistics, information and financial. Optimal performance emerges with a floor-area ratio 2.5-3.5, building-coverage ratio of 25%-45%, and mean building height approximate to 30 m. Mean building volume shows a bimodal effect: both compact (<5,000 m(3)) and mid-large (approximate to 50,000 m(3)) structures strengthen integrated flow efficiency, whereas intermediate volumes depress it. The framework achieved higher predictive accuracy than Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost), Random Forest, and Ordinary Least Squares regression, with an R-2 of 0.82. It also revealed spatial trade-offs among flows. Findings advocate context-sensitive density control, balanced height regimes and diversified massing to optimize hub performance. By coupling urban morphology with explainable AI, the study delivers actionable thresholds and replicable tools for data-driven, multi-flow urban hub planning.
