TI  - Interpretable machine learning-assisted mid-infrared spectroscopy for qualitative and quantitative quality assessment of flat green tea
T2  - FOOD CONTROL
AB  - The identification of the geographical origin of tea is a long-standing challenge. However, green and recyclable identification methods applicable to tea geographic origin are still missing. Therefore, this study aims to explore the feasibility of mid-infrared spectroscopy (MIR) and machine learning for geographic origin traceability and component detection in flat green tea. One hundred flat tea samples with 50 geographical indication (GI) and 50 non-GI labels of Longjing tea were evaluated. Significant differences (p < 0.05) were observed in both tea polyphenols and free amino acids between GI and non-GI samples. The nonlinear SVM model based on MIR achieved accurate identification for 34 tea samples with an accuracy of 97.06 %. The nonlinear SVR and linear CARS-PLSR models achieved the quantification of tea polyphenols and amino acids with RMSE values of 0.78 % and 0.09 %, respectively. The SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) values further indicated that the wavenumbers at 2196 (negatively contributing), 1988 (positively contributing) and 2181 cm(-1) (positively contributing) were dominated in predicting the geographical origin, tea polyphenols and amino acids, respectively, thereby contributing to the accuracy of the models. This study offers a reliable model for the traceability of geographic origin in agricultural products.
