TI  - Real-Time Strength Monitoring and Prediction of Recycled Aggregate Concrete Using PZT Sensors and WOA-XGBoost
T2  - IEEE SENSORS JOURNAL
AB  - Recycled aggregate concrete (RAC) has been widely adopted in construction due to its ability to convert construction waste into new aggregates. However, its lower strength compared to ordinary concrete necessitates real-time monitoring of strength evolution for quality control. In this research, Pb-lead zirconate titanate (PZT) sensors were embedded at the center of RAC specimens with recycled aggregate replacement ratios of 0%, 30%, 60%, and 100%. A novel electromechanical impedance (EMI) technique was utilized to monitor conductance parameters, complemented by root mean square deviation (RMSD) to evaluate the strength evolution of RAC. Furthermore, the relationships between conductance, frequency, and compressive strength were systematically analyzed. To enhance the predictive performance of the extreme gradient boosting (XGBoost) algorithm, the whale optimization algorithm (WOA) was employed for hyperparameter optimization. Leveraging a dataset of 91 experimental samples, a multifactor coupling model for RAC strength prediction was developed, integrating key variables such as water-binder ratio, recycled aggregate content, curing temperature, curing humidity, curing age, and RMSD. The prediction results of the WOA-XGBoost model were compared with those of XGBoost, gradient boosting decision tree (GBDT), and random forest (RF), demonstrating the highest accuracy, with ${R}<^>{{2}}$ of 0.949 and the lowest prediction error. Furthermore, the Shapley additive explanations (SHAP) method was introduced to elucidate the influence of input characteristics on prediction results, thereby enhancing the interpretation and analysis of the model decision process. This research offers substantial theoretical underpinning and practical insights for the application of RAC in construction contexts.
