TI  - Carbonation depth assessment of recycled aggregate concrete: An application of conformal prediction intervals
T2  - EXPERT SYSTEMS WITH APPLICATIONS
AB  - Accurate prediction of carbonation depth in recycled aggregate concrete (RAC) is essential for assessing the durability and long-term performance of concrete structures. This study systematically evaluated various conformal prediction methods through extensive numerical experiments, emphasizing their ability to generate prediction intervals with optimal coverage and interval width. Weighted methods, such as Weighted Jackknife+ (WJ+) and Weighted Cross-Validation+ (WCV+), consistently produced more efficient prediction intervals without compromising coverage, particularly when applied to tree-based models like Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGB) and Gradient Boosting (GB). The importance of feature selection, model choice, and method selection in achieving reliable and efficient prediction intervals was highlighted. SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) analysis identified exposure time, compressive strength, CO2 concentration, and cement content as the primary determinants of carbonation depth. Additionally, a user-friendly graphical user interface was developed to facilitate the prediction of carbonation depth progression in RAC over time. This research provides a significant advancement in the accurate prediction of carbonation depth, contributing to the sustainable management of concrete infrastructures.
