TI  - Creep behavior evaluation of recycled aggregate concrete using machine learning technology
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - This study presents the application of machine learning technologies in the creep behavior evaluation of recycled aggregate concrete (termed as RAC). The Back-propagation Neural Network (BPNN), the Whale Optimization Algorithm (WOA), and the Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) methods were used in the predicted model establishment of the RAC creep, relatively. A comprehensive dataset, comprising 291 groups of in-situ and laboratory tests of RAC specimens collected from published articles and laboratory, was used for the model development and validation. The optimal hyper-parameters were obtained by using the random search and the k-fold cross-validation methods. Subsequently, the factor correlation analysis and the importance analysis were conducted to evaluate the influence of the key factors on the predicted creep results. The results show that the proposed XGBoost with hyper-parameter optimization exhibits high performance in predicting creep behavior of RAC materials. The outcome of this research offers a potential solution for predicting creep behavior of RAC materials that undergo long-term loading.
