TI  - Leveraging data-driven strategy for redesigning the tubular fixed bed propane dehydrogenation reactor
T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF HYDROGEN ENERGY
AB  - Propane dehydrogenation is a mainstream propylene production technology with high economic efficiency, low oil dependence, and clean energy hydrogen production. However, challenges exist in constructing large-scale database for reactor design and optimization of propane dehydrogenation. This study leverages a data-driven strategy for reactor redesign and optimization. Firstly, an artificial neural network (ANN) is developed based on Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) simulation to evaluate the weight of operating parameters with Shapley values. The results indicate that flow rate most significantly impacts propane conversion. A recycle-based redesign approach to increase propane residence time is proposed. How to improve the reactor performance becomes a multi-objective optimization problem with 4 variables and 3 objectives. A hybrid optimization method combining the ANN and Non-dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm-II (NSGA-II) is used to obtain the Pareto front for compromising among three objectives. The application of the data-driven model can improve reactant utilization, effectively save experimental resources, and reduce about 96.87% of the calculation time. The application of the data-driven strategy in this study underscores its effectiveness and efficiency in reactor redesign and optimization, which can be used to guide the practical chemical production process.
