TI  - A New insight for CO2 sequestration with heavy metal immobilization by calcium recycling using interpretative machine learning
T2  - CHEMICAL ENGINEERING JOURNAL
AB  - Accelerated carbonation of calcium-containing wastes has garnered significant attention for its potential in CO2 sequestration and heavy metal risk mitigation. Municipal solid waste incineration fly ash (MSWI FA), a typical calcium-rich alkaline hazardous waste, presents a challenge due to its complex composition and process parameters, making prediction and evaluation difficult. CO2 sequestration mass and overall pollution toxicity index for quantitative predictions were utilized, employing eight machine learning models and the Shapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) algorithm to analyze the synergistic mechanisms. Among the models, Gradient Boosting (GB) model excelled in forecasting the CO2 storage capacity and heavy metal risks associated with FA, achieving Test_R2 values above 0.95. The material parameters in FA (84.2 % of the importance) had a significantly higher impact on carbon sequestration than the process parameters (15.8 %). In particular, MgO and Fe2O3 are the two most important material parameters, negatively impacting CO2 storage, while CaO has a biggest positive effect. Additionally, lower initial leaching concentrations of Zn, Pb, and total Cu content negatively impacted the environmental risk reduction in carbonated FA. Notably, increased CO2 storage enhanced the stabilization of heavy metals, significantly lowering the risk of heavy metal leaching when the carbon sequestration exceeded 180 g-CO2/kg-FA.
