TI  - Predictive modeling and graphical user interface-based interpretation of valuable metal leaching efficiency from coal gangue using machine learning
T2  - MINERALS ENGINEERING
AB  - Coal gangue, a major solid waste generated from coal mining and processing, contains significant quantities of valuable metals such as aluminum (Al), iron (Fe), lithium (Li), and gallium (Ga). Efficient and sustainable recovery of these metals is critical for minimizing environmental impacts and maximizing resource utilization. In this study, a combined roasting-acid leaching process was investigated for the selective extraction of valuable metals from coal gangue. To enhance process understanding and predictive capability, interpretable machine learning (ML) models were employed to model the leaching efficiencies based on key parameters, including gangue composition, roasting temperature, acid concentration, leaching time, liquid-to-solid ratio, and leaching temperature. Among several ML models, gradient boosting regression (GBR) demonstrated the highest predictive performance (R-2 > 0.96 for all target metals). Feature importance and Shapley additive explanations (SHAP) analyses identified roasting and leaching temperatures as the most influential factors affecting metal recovery. Furthermore, a graphical user interface (GUI) was developed to facilitate process optimization based on the trained GBR model. This integrated approach offers a robust tool for optimizing the recovery of critical metals from coal gangue. The proposed process reduces the environmental footprint of coal gangue disposal and supports sustainable metal recycling. It thus contributes to minimizing ecological impacts in the mining sector.
