TI  - Integrating Raman spectroscopy and interpretable deep learning: A multimodal approach for plastic material identification
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMICAL ENGINEERING
AB  - Rapid and accurate identification of biodegradable and conventional plastics is crucial for sustainable waste management. Raman spectroscopy provides informative molecular fingerprints. However, background variation and overlapping Raman bands in practical measurements can limit the performance of traditional machine learning and single-modality deep learning models when they rely on only a few selected spectral features. In this study, a multimodal deep learning framework combining Raman spectroscopy with interpretable analysis is proposed. The method extracts band parameters including position, intensity, area and full width at half maximum (FWHM) from baseline-corrected Raman spectra, and simultaneously converts the spectra into Gramian Angular Difference Field (GADF) images to preserve both local and global spectral patterns. A dual-branch convolutional neural network (CNN) is designed to learn from the numerical and image modalities, achieving a classification accuracy of 98.36 % across 38 types of plastics including both biodegradable and conventional materials. Interpretability is assessed through t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE) visualization, SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) values and Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM) heatmaps, confirming that the fused representation enhances feature separability and links model attention to chemically meaningful Raman bands. The proposed approach provides a transparent and high-performance solution for automated plastic identification and recycling applications.
