TI  - Hybrid data-driven optimization framework for sustainable concrete incorporating micro ground granulated blast furnace slag, treated construction and demolition waste, and recycled plastic fibres
T2  - APPLIED SOFT COMPUTING
AB  - The research introduces a new hybrid-based data driven optimization method of sustainable high-performance concrete utilizing micro ground granulated blast furnace slag (GGBS), treated construction and demolition waste (CDW) and recycled plastic fibres. In contrast to previous articles that involved empirical testing, individual ma chine learning models, the current study brings together random forest (RF) prediction, Gradient-based bounded optimization (L-BFGS-B), SHapley additive explanations (SHAP) to interpretability, and response surface method ology (RSM) for validation as one unified platform. The compressive strength of thirty-six experimental mixtures of M40 concrete with different percentage restrictions of GGBS (0%-30%), CDW aggregates (50%-100%), and PET fibres (0.3%-1.2%). The RF model demonstrated good predictive accuracy (R2 = 0.994), whereas the (L-BFGS-B) found the best mixtures that included 100% CDW and moderate levels of plastic components, and predicted strengths of 49 MPa. SHAP analysis presented clear information about the influence of each vari able, which is important because GGBS and CDW interactions are significant, and RSM proved the presence of nonlinear interaction patterns. The experimentally verified mixtures of L-BFGS-B-optimized exhibited comparable compressive strengths to the experiment maximum, and significant environmental benefits. In this study, a repro ducible, interpretable, and sustainability-based optimization approach is provided, and the scientific knowledge and practice of data-driven green concrete mix design are promoted.
