TI  - Hybrid machine learning and multi-objective optimization for intelligent design of green and low-carbon concrete
T2  - SUSTAINABLE MATERIALS AND TECHNOLOGIES
AB  - The increasing utilization of recycled aggregates and supplementary cementitious materials in green and lowcarbon concrete production demands advanced methods to predict and optimize the performance, yet challenges remain in performance, sustainability, and cost trade-offs. In this study, a comprehensive database for recycled aggregate concrete using supplementary cementitious materials was established, and a hybrid framework integrating machine learning and multi-objective optimization was proposed. Results demonstrated that Sparrow Search Algorithm optimized models significantly outperformed base models, with Sparrow Search Algorithm-Extreme Gradient Boosting achieving superior accuracy with R2 values of 0.9403 for slump, 0.9428 for compressive strength, 0.9017 for total charge passed. Shapley additive explanation analysis quantified feature contributions, revealing fly ash/superplasticizer dosage, effective water-binder ratio, and cement dosage as dominant factors for slump, compressive strength, and total charge passed, respectively. Furthermore, the advanced third-generation non-dominated sorting genetic algorithm and the technique for order of preference by similarity to ideal solution were integrated to optimize mix designs, balancing compressive strength, carbon emissions, and material costs. Sensitivity analysis highlighted the impacts of recycled aggregates and supplementary cementitious material replacement ratios, and transportation distances on performance, sustainability, and cost-effectiveness. This study is the establishment of this robust framework, which provides a systematic, data-driven roadmap for designing high-performance, low-carbon, and cost-effective concrete, thereby offering a viable pathway toward sustainable infrastructure.
