TI  - Axial compressive capacity prediction of coal gangue concrete-filled steel tube stub columns: Genetic programming-augmented code calibration and Bayesian-optimized machine learning
T2  - STRUCTURES
AB  - The growing demand for green construction materials in building engineering has driven innovations in sustainable structural design. This demand has further intensified the urgency of coal gangue (CG) recycling, propelling the development of coal gangue concrete-filled steel tube (CGCFST) columns. However, existing design codes for predicting axial compressive capacity suffer from limited accuracy and applicability, and they fail to adequately account for the effects of CG aggregate replacement ratios. To address the aforementioned limitations, this study develops a genetic programming-augmented code calibration approach combined with Bayesian-optimized machine learning (ML). Leveraging experimental data from 96 circular CGCFST specimens, we establish a comprehensive database incorporating seven critical parameters-including CG aggregate replacement ratios for both coarse and fine aggregates. Systematic evaluation of 18 existing models through TOPSIS analysis exposes significant underestimation (up to 40 % errors) in conventional code formulations, particularly in accounting for CG substitution effects. Through genetic programming-symbolic regression (GPSR), we enhance four design codes, achieving a 63.61 % RMSE reduction in the AIJ-optimized model via evolutionary algorithm-driven code calibration. Parallel development of eight Bayesian-optimized machine learning models identifies CatBoost as the superior predictor (R2=0.988), with SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) interpretability analysis quantifying how CG replacement ratios dynamically alter feature importance hierarchies through nonlinear interactions. The GP-SR calibrated codes provide physics-informed equations compatible with engineering practice, while the Bayesian-optimized ML models establish new accuracy benchmarks. This dual approach combines theoretical interpretability and data-driven prediction, offering effective solutions to boost CG aggregate applications in building engineering and sustainable structural design.
