TI  - Multi-objective mix optimization of geopolymer recycled aggregate concrete using prior knowledge embedded neural network and evolutionary algorithm
T2  - ENGINEERING APPLICATIONS OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE
AB  - Geopolymer recycled aggregate concrete (GPRC) is a promising construction material that reduces carbon emissions and resource consumption. However, its application is limited by the lack of an effective mix design methodology. This study developed a prior Knowledge Embedded Neural Network (KENN) by incorporating governing equations into the neural network, resulting in a high-precision compressive strength prediction model that effectively captures the complex nonlinear interactions among GPRC mix components. The trained compressive strength prediction model was then embedded as an objective function within the Non-dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm II (NSGA-II) for multi-objective mix optimization, from which a mix design method was constructed that maximizes 28-day compressive strength while simultaneously minimizing costs, CO2 emission, and energy consumption. The results demonstrate that the KENN-based prediction model achieved a high coefficient of determination of 0.9126 on the testing set. Feature importance and Shapley Additive Explanations (SHAP) value analyses identified the recycled concrete powder replacement ratio, sand ratio, slag content, fine aggregate-to-precursor materials ratio, and recycled fine aggregate replacement ratio as the primary factors influencing the compressive strength of GPRC. Additionally, a well-defined Pareto front of the optimized GPRC mixtures was successfully constructed. Experimental validation of mixtures target strength grades of C30, C50, and C70 demonstrated that the compressive strength prediction errors were maintained within 5.0 %, verifying the precision of the proposed mix design. This study offers an innovative and practical solution for the efficient and sustainable design of GPRC, with potential applicability to the optimization of other eco-friendly concrete mixtures.
