TI  - Explainable Prediction of Compressive Strength and Elastic Modulus for Concrete Containing Waste Foundry Sand Using Bayesian-Optimized XGBoost with 10-Fold Cross-Validation
T2  - JOURNAL OF SUSTAINABLE METALLURGY
AB  - Waste foundry sand (WFS), generated by the metal casting industry, is commonly disposed of in landfills, posing a significant environmental hazard. Recycling WFS to replace natural fine aggregate in concrete is a feasible solution to mitigate its ecological impact. In this study, the compressive strength (CS) and elastic modulus (Ea) of sustainable concrete containing WFS are estimated by the extreme gradient boosting (XGBoost) algorithm. Bayesian optimization with 10-fold cross-validation is applied to fine-tune the hyperparameters of XGBoost. The outcomes reveal that the optimized XGBoost generalize well in 10-fold cross-validation, yielding average coefficient of determination (R2) values of 0.889 for CS and 0.951 for Ea. High prediction accuracy is also achieved on the testing dataset, with R2 values of 0.940 for CS and 0.995 for Ea. Furthermore, individual conditional exception (ICE) plot, partial dependence plot (PDP), and Shapley additive explanation (SHAP), are utilized to shed light on global and local insights into the models. Results from these interpretable techniques suggest that WFS-related variables hold relatively low importance to the model outputs, and as long as the ratio of WFS to fine aggregate does not exceed 0.35 (or 0.1), the CS (or Ea) will not be severely compromised and might even experience slight enhancements. Additionally, an online graphical user interface (GUI) is also created based on the optimized models to facilitate the estimation of CS or Ea for WFS-containing concrete.
