TI  - A data-driven method for the design and calculation of recycled concrete mix proportions based on carbon footprint
T2  - MATERIALS TODAY COMMUNICATIONS
AB  - Reasonable mix ratio design of recycled aggregate concrete (RAC) helps to promote its popularization and application in engineering structures. In this paper, a data-driven approach combined with a multi-objective optimization search algorithm for the design of RAC proportion is proposed to address the shortcomings of traditional design methods and the gap of data-driven approach in the field of RAC proportion research. Using 502 sets of data, four models for predicting and interpreting the CS characteristics of RAC were developed and the model with the best predictive performance was interpreted using SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) values. Then, the CS, carbon footprint of RAC and economic cost were used as objective functions, and a multiobjective particle swarm optimization method based on a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model multiobjective optimization-seeking algorithm was proposed to obtain the optimal mix ratio under specific conditions. The results showed that: the data-driven approach was effective in predicting the CS of RAC; the CS prediction model for RAC using the LSTM algorithm showed the best performance with an R-value of 0.926. With the optimization model created in this work, it was possible to improve the mix ratios of the three selected objective functions with respect to the RAC; compared to the function that only considered CS and cost, the carbon footprint objective function that considered the Pareto-optimal solution reduces the carbon footprint by 5 % compared to the function considering only CS and cost. This approach helps to find the mix ratio with the lowest cost and carbon footprint of RAC while meeting the actual engineering requirements.
