TI  - Design of recycled concrete mix proportions based on ensemble algorithms and multi-objective optimization
T2  - CONSTRUCTION AND BUILDING MATERIALS
AB  - This study proposes a multi-objective optimization of mix proportion design for Recycled Aggregate Concrete (RAC). Based on 749 sets of test data, the model is established by combining machine learning methods with genetic algorithms. According to the concrete mix proportion theory, this study selects nine input features, including the dosages of water, cement, natural coarse aggregate (NCA), and recycled coarse aggregate (RCA), along with the maximum particle size of RCA (Dinax), water absorption rate (W_RCA), and apparent density (p-RCA); the output features are the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) and splitting tensile strength (STS). Then five machine learning algorithms and one neural network algorithm are employed to capture the nonlinear mapping relationships between the two mechanical strengths and the concrete mix proportions. The results demonstrated that the Gradient Boosting Decision Tree (GBDT) model exhibited superior generalization and robustness in predicting both UCS and STS, achieving more accurate predictions with R2 values of 0.99 and 0.92 for the training and testing sets of UCS, and R2 values of 0.98 and 0.77 for the training and testing sets of STS, respectively. An interpret-ability analysis using the Shapley Additive Explanations (SHAP) approach revealed that the dosage of cement is the most influential factor on both UCS and STS, in line with the traditional watercement ratio rule. Under specification limits, Non-dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm II (NSGA-II) was applied to solve the tri-objective problem involving UCS, STS and CO2 emissions, yielding a set of Pareto front optimal solutions. The Pareto Front can be divided into priority zones according to different engineering demands, and a single optimal solution can be selected via Technique for Order Preference by Similarity to an Ideal Solution (TOPSIS) with weights. Validation through experimental-optimization data comparison proved the GBDT-NSGAII model's rational material usage and performance improvement in mix design.
