TI  - Eco-friendly intelligent mixture design of glass powder concrete: A life cycle perspective with hybrid machine learning and generative adversarial networks
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - Waste glass powder (GP), as a sustainable supplementary cementitious material, has been demonstrated to mitigate the CO2 emissions and reduce the economic costs associated with conventional concrete production using pure Portland cement. However, traditional approaches often fail to optimize the performance and sustainability metrics of glass powder concrete (GPC) due to intricate component coupling mechanisms. In this study, an intelligent mixture design framework for GPC was developed, integrating hybrid machine learning (ML) models with multi-objective optimization (MOO) techniques. This framework was designed to enhance the comprehensive performance of GPC while minimizing environmental impact (EI) and life cycle cost (LCC). A database comprising 1279 experimental samples was compiled, with Generative Adversarial Networks (GAN) employed for data augmentation to bolster robustness and prediction accuracy. Results demonstrate that GAN-augmented data slightly improves the R2 value of XGB model by 1.63 %. The hybrid ML algorithm AVOA-XGB exhibits superior prediction accuracy, achieving R2 values of 0.958, 0.952, and 0.954 for slump, compressive strength, and total charge passed, respectively. Feature analysis, using Shapley Additive Explanations (SHAP) and three-dimensional Partial Dependence Plots (3D-PDP), reveals the significant influence of GP on concrete performance and its pronounced interactions with other components. The MOO model effectively delineates the Pareto frontier for multi-objective functions, yielding an optimal mixture design. Sensitivity analysis indicates that a suitable GP replacement rate of less than 50 % markedly enhances GPC performance compared to pure cement system, delivering substantial EI and LCC benefits. Finally, an interactive GPC performance prediction and mixture design system has been developed, showcasing the promising application prospects of GPC as a sustainable construction material.
